<title>CHILE: Miners say Escondida hires anti-strike contractees.</title>
<headline>Miners say Escondida hires anti-strike contractees.</headline>
<dateline>SANTIAGO 1997-04-28</dateline>
<text>
<p>Escondida copper mine has contracted temporary workers to try to make up for production lost to a strike, a union official said.</p>
<p>&quot;They're bringing in scabs,&quot; said Renato Munoz, a union official at the Escondida workers union headquarters in the northern Chilean city of Antofagasta. He did not say how many temporary workers had been hired.</p>
<p>Escondida had no new comment on the strike by about 15 percent of its work force of 2,000 people. The company has said the walkout affected operations slightly since it began April 19 but that it had no effect on production, and a spokesman said there was no change in that situation.</p>
<p>--Roger Atwood, Santiago newsroom +56-2-6995595 x211</p>
